 cultural fields. Thanks to their broad networks, outstanding managerial skills, and abundant financial resources, these salt merchants were ideal agents for selecting and producing objects for imperial use. In contrast to the typical caricature of merchants as mimics of the literati, these wealthy businessmen became respected individuals who played a crucial role in the political, economic, social, and cultural world of eighteenth-century China. Their life experiences illustrate the dynamic relationship between the Manchu and Han, central and local, and humans and objects in Chinese history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aManchuszChinaxKings and rulersxHistoryy18th century. 0aMaterial culturezChinaxHistoryy18th century. 0aMerchantsxSocial networkszChinaxHistoryy18th century. 0aMerchantszChinazHuizhou DiquxHistoryy18th century. 4aHuizhou. 4aLower Yangzi valley. 4aManchu. 4aQianlong emperor. 4aQing dynasty. 4acourt. 4aluxury consumption. 4amaterial culture. 4asalt merchants. 4asalt monopoly. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503600799zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503600799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503600799.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles